<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="40" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,474,825]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,474,500]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Coloration cream white, with diffuse pink patches, and black spots, mainly on the tegmina (
<figureCitation box="[1319,1424,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="41.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-22@41.[153,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURE 23. Yungasacris species. A, G–H. Y. multa. Male habitus, cerci in dorsal and lateral view respectively. B–C. Y. grata grata cerci in dorsal and lateral view. D. Y. grata rara cerci in lateral view. E–F. Y. peruviana cerci in dorsal and lateral view respectively. (Figs. B–F. after Rehn, 1950, Figs. D, G–H. after Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Gorochov, 2013)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876271/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Fig. 23A</figureCitation>
). Vertex smooth, sub-elevated, the distal contour rounded in lateral view. Hind femora ventrally armed from the mesal region to the apex with triangular lamellar spines. Tegmina exceeding apex of abdomen for more than half their length in males and about half their length in females, outline elongate or lanceolate, slightly narrowed in distal half, apical margin obliquely truncate (
<figureCitation box="[533,639,618,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="41.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-22@41.[153,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURE 23. Yungasacris species. A, G–H. Y. multa. Male habitus, cerci in dorsal and lateral view respectively. B–C. Y. grata grata cerci in dorsal and lateral view. D. Y. grata rara cerci in lateral view. E–F. Y. peruviana cerci in dorsal and lateral view respectively. (Figs. B–F. after Rehn, 1950, Figs. D, G–H. after Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Gorochov, 2013)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876271/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Fig. 23A</figureCitation>
). Male cerci with a thick base and an elongated, compressed, and subcultriform prolongation, and a flattened and triangular process on the internal side, mesial region concave and with an excavated appearance (
<figureCitation box="[447,597,690,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="41.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-22@41.[153,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURE 23. Yungasacris species. A, G–H. Y. multa. Male habitus, cerci in dorsal and lateral view respectively. B–C. Y. grata grata cerci in dorsal and lateral view. D. Y. grata rara cerci in lateral view. E–F. Y. peruviana cerci in dorsal and lateral view respectively. (Figs. B–F. after Rehn, 1950, Figs. D, G–H. after Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Gorochov, 2013)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876271/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Figs. 23B–H</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor twice as long as the pronotal disc, uniformly curved, in distal region dorsal and ventral margins serrulate and laterally with numerous spinules, apex narrowly rounded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
